04475nam a22007335i 9783110613636DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022945601  a97831106136367 a10.1515/97831106136362doi  a(DE-B1597)498069  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0020002bisacsh1 aTsiamis, Costas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlague in Byzantine Times :bA Medico-historical Study /cCostas Tsiamis. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (247 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMedicine in the Medieval Mediterranean ,x2569-314X ;v9  aDiss.cUniversity of Athensd2010.00tFrontmatter -- tForeword Ancient Epidemics The Necessity of a Multidisciplinary Approach -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 What is Plague? -- tChapter 2 Inside the Molecular World of Yersinia pestis -- tChapter 3 Aggravating Factors of Plague -- tChapter 4 Plague-resembling Epidemics from Antiquity to Byzantium -- tChapter 5 First Plague Pandemic -- tChapter 6 The Second Plague Pandemic -- tChapter 7 Analysis of the First Pandemic -- tChapter 8 Analysis of the Second Pandemic -- tChapter 9 Theories on the Disappearance of Plague (751–1346) -- tEpilogue -- tLists of Tables, Figures and Maps -- tBibliography -- tGlossary -- tIndex of Names and Places -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe lack of reliable demographic data for Byzantine cities raises questions as to the actual rate of expansion and mortality of plague. This essentially leads to the question of change and progress of the nature of infectious diseases in that period. Also, the analysis of the written sources raised a series of questions, mainly epidemiological in nature: the entry points and spreading of the disease in the Mediterranean, the epidemic dynamics as well as the evolution of the microbial agent of plague, i.e. Yersinia pestis. The present study offers a substantial explanation for the outbreaks of plague that struck Byzantium by exploring the multiple factors that caused or triggered epidemics. The study covers the entire period extending from the beginning of the Byzantine Empire until its fall in 1453, which was marked by two major pandemics, namely the Plague of Justinian and the Black Death. All known primary sources were collected and grouped from a spatiotemporal perspective, so as to retrace the unfolding of the two pandemics. The focus of the research shifts from known historical frameworks to ones of human activities, endemic foci and natural environment of the era as risk factors of the outbreaks.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 4aByzantinische Zeit. 4aEpidemiologie. 4aPest. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aBlack Death.  aByzantine Empire.  aHistorical epidemiology.  aJustinian Plague.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z97831107668200 cEPUBz97831106112500 cprintz978311061119940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311061363640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110613636423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110613636/original  a978-3-11-076682-0  DG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1b2022  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK